To find the inverse of a 2x2 matrix A = \begin{bmatrix}a & b \\ c & d\end{bmatrix}, we can use the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{ad - bc} \begin{bmatrix}d & -b \\ -c & a\end{bmatrix}

In this case, A = \begin{bmatrix}2 & 3 \\ 5 & 7\end{bmatrix}, so a = 2, b = 3, c = 5, and d = 7.

First, we need to find the determinant (ad - bc):

Determinant = (2 * 7) - (3 * 5) = 14 - 15 = -1

Now, we can find the inverse using the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{-1} \begin{bmatrix}7 & -3 \\ -5 & 2\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}-7 & 3 \\ 5 & -2\end{bmatrix}

So, the inverse of matrix A is:

A⁻¹ = \begin{bmatrix}-7 & 3 \\ 5 & -2\end{bmatrix}
